There's a y dz and there's also a free z squared.

00:05:38.120 --> 00:05:41.140
You can get this either by implicit differentiation

00:05:41.140 --> 00:05:46.140
and the product rule, or you can get this just by putting here

00:05:46.140 --> 00:05:49.620
and here the partial derivatives of this with respect

00:05:49.620 --> 00:05:50.620
to x, y, and z.

00:05:54.040 --> 00:05:55.940
Any questions about how I got this?

00:05:57.760 --> 00:05:58.440
No, okay.

00:06:00.240 --> 00:06:02.360
So, now, what do I do with this?

00:06:03.060 --> 00:06:05.880
Well, this represents somehow variations of g.

00:06:07.360 --> 00:06:10.600
But, well, I've set this thing equal to 8,

00:06:11.580 --> 00:06:13.180
and 8 is a constant.

00:06:13.980 --> 00:06:15.000
So, it doesn't change.

00:06:16.000 --> 00:06:22.040
So, in fact, well, we can set this to zero,

00:06:30.000 --> 00:06:32.840
because, well, they call this g,

00:06:35.520 --> 00:06:41.320
then g equals 8 is constant, that means we set dg equal to zero.

00:06:43.340 --> 00:06:43.340


00:06:45.040 --> 00:06:49.260
So, now, let's just plug in some values at this point

00:06:53.400 --> 00:06:57.720
that tells us, well, so if x equals 2, that's 4 dx,

00:06:58.860 --> 00:07:05.620
plus z is 1, so dy, plus y plus free z squared

00:07:06.200 --> 00:07:09.960
should be 6 dz equals 0.

00:07:11.300 --> 00:07:15.780
And now, this equation here tells us about a relation

00:07:15.780 --> 00:07:18.160
between the changes in x, y, and z, near that point.

00:07:18.600 --> 00:07:20.620
It tells us how, if you change x and y,

00:07:21.140 --> 00:07:25.380
well, how z will change, or it tells you, actually,

00:07:25.940 --> 00:07:27.620
anything you might want to know about the relations

00:07:27.620 --> 00:07:28.480
between these variables.

00:07:29.660 --> 00:07:32.240
So, for example, you can move dz to that side,

00:07:32.240 --> 00:07:34.580
and then express dz in terms of dx and dy,

00:07:34.960 --> 00:07:36.860
or you can move dy to that side,

00:07:37.380 --> 00:07:40.280
and express dy in terms of dx and dz, and so on.

00:07:41.020 --> 00:07:42.480
It tells you, at the level of derivatives,

00:07:43.160 --> 00:07:45.720
how each of the variables depends on the two of us.

00:07:49.020 --> 00:07:52.220
Okay, so just to clarify this,

00:07:55.540 --> 00:07:59.100
if we want to view z as a function of x and y,

00:08:00.620 --> 00:08:04.060
then what we will do is we'll just move the dz

00:08:04.060 --> 00:08:07.940
to the other side, and it will tell us dz equals

00:08:09.380 --> 00:08:13.600
minus 1 over 6 times 4 dx plus dy.

00:08:17.440 --> 00:08:22.140
And so, that should tell you that partial z

00:08:22.220 --> 00:08:26.260
over partial x is minus 4 over 6,

00:08:26.380 --> 00:08:30.140
well, that's minus 2 thirds, and partial z

00:08:30.140 --> 00:08:34.440
over partial y is going to be minus 1, 6.

00:08:39.900 --> 00:08:41.700
Another way to think about this,

00:08:42.540 --> 00:08:44.980
when we compute partial z over partial x,

00:08:45.720 --> 00:08:48.900
that means that, actually, we keep y constant.

00:08:50.300 --> 00:08:54.060
Okay, let me actually add some subtitles here.

00:08:54.840 --> 00:08:57.000
So here, that means we keep y constant,

00:08:59.680 --> 00:09:03.200
and so if we keep y constant, another way to think about it

00:09:03.200 --> 00:09:07.060
is we set dy to zero.

00:09:07.460 --> 00:09:08.960
We set dy equals zero.

00:09:09.620 --> 00:09:13.900
So if we do that, we get dx equals negative 4, 6 dx.

00:09:15.360 --> 00:09:18.320
That tells us the rate of change of z with respect to x.

00:09:19.840 --> 00:09:28.300
Here, we set x constant, so that means we set dx equal to zero.

00:09:29.500 --> 00:09:33.920
And if we set dx equal to zero, then we have dz equals negative 1, 6th of dy,

00:09:34.260 --> 00:09:36.540
that tells us the rate of change of z with respect to y.

00:09:39.020 --> 00:09:41.140
Okay, any questions about that?

00:09:46.260 --> 00:09:46.840
No?

00:09:48.860 --> 00:09:49.800
What? Yes?

00:09:50.900 --> 00:09:56.020
Can you explain why we have run dt when dx and dy into partial?

00:09:56.500 --> 00:09:58.800
Yes, okay, let me explain that again.

00:09:59.480 --> 00:10:02.880
So we found an expression for dz in terms of dx and dy,

00:10:03.380 --> 00:10:08.040
that means that this thing is the total differential of z

00:10:08.560 --> 00:10:09.000
and z is the total differential of z,

00:10:09.000 --> 00:10:10.200
so that means that we have run dt as a function of x and y.

00:10:11.700 --> 00:10:14.840
Okay, and so the coefficients of dx and dy are the partial.

00:10:16.420 --> 00:10:18.100
Or another way to think about it,

00:10:18.480 --> 00:10:20.460
if you want to know partial z partial x,

00:10:20.660 --> 00:10:22.200
it means you set y to be constant.

00:10:22.680 --> 00:10:25.860
Setting y to be constant means that you will put zero

00:10:25.860 --> 00:10:27.320
in the place of dy.

00:10:27.820 --> 00:10:31.580
So you'll be left with dz equals minus 4, 6 dx.

00:10:32.580 --> 00:10:35.780
And that will give you the rate of change of z with respect to x

00:10:35.780 --> 00:10:37.160
when you keep y constant.

00:10:38.420 --> 00:10:38.420


00:10:41.760 --> 00:10:44.000
So various ways to think about this,

00:10:44.160 --> 00:10:46.300
but hopefully it makes sense.

00:10:52.480 --> 00:10:53.000
Okay.

00:10:54.980 --> 00:10:58.200
So how do we think about this in general?

00:11:04.000 --> 00:11:10.620
Well, if we know that g of x, y, z equals constant,

00:11:15.380 --> 00:11:24.900
then dg, which is g sub x dx plus g sub y dy plus g sub z dz,

00:11:25.840 --> 00:11:27.680
should be set equal to zero.

00:11:28.480 --> 00:11:28.960
Okay.

00:11:31.180 --> 00:11:35.340
And now we can solve for whichever variable we want to express

00:11:35.340 --> 00:11:36.340
in terms of the others.

00:11:38.340 --> 00:11:42.520
So, for example, if we care about z as a function of x and y,

00:11:47.500 --> 00:11:47.980
it's...

00:11:53.120 --> 00:12:01.240
We'll get that dz is negative g sub x of g sub z dx,

00:12:02.420 --> 00:12:08.440
sorry, minus g sub y of g sub z dy.

00:12:09.720 --> 00:12:12.700
And so if we want partial z,

00:12:18.000 --> 00:12:19.120
then we can solve for other partial x.

00:12:20.600 --> 00:12:24.360
Well, so one way is just to say that's going to be the coefficient

00:12:24.360 --> 00:12:27.540
of dx in here, or just to write down the other way.

00:12:28.620 --> 00:12:31.360
We are setting y equals constant.

00:12:33.560 --> 00:12:36.920
So that means we set dy equal to zero.

00:12:38.920 --> 00:12:39.120
Okay.

00:12:39.300 --> 00:12:47.220
And then we get dz equals negative g sub x of our g sub z dx.

00:12:47.980 --> 00:12:55.120
So that means partial z of our partial x is minus gx over gz.

00:12:56.200 --> 00:12:58.580
And see, that's a very counter-intuitive formula,

00:12:58.960 --> 00:13:01.900
because you have this minus sign that you somehow probably

00:13:01.900 --> 00:13:05.960
couldn't have seen come, you know, if you hadn't actually derived things

00:13:05.960 --> 00:13:06.380
this way.

00:13:07.800 --> 00:13:12.780
I mean, it's pretty surprising to see that minus sign come out of nowhere

00:13:12.780 --> 00:13:13.940
the first time you see it.

00:13:18.440 --> 00:13:18.860
Okay.

00:13:20.300 --> 00:13:25.400
So now we know how to find the rate of change of constrained variables

00:13:25.400 --> 00:13:26.620
with respect to each other.

00:13:28.780 --> 00:13:30.680
You can apply the same to find, you know,

00:13:31.200 --> 00:13:33.920
if you want partial x, partial y or any of them, you can do it.

00:13:36.700 --> 00:13:38.200
Any questions so far?

00:13:40.580 --> 00:13:41.120
No?

00:13:44.360 --> 00:13:44.900
