00:13:47.500 --> 00:13:55.420
So before we proceed further, I should probably expose some

00:13:55.420 --> 00:13:57.580
problem with the notations that we have so far.

00:13:59.400 --> 00:14:01.620
So let me try to get you a bit confused.

00:14:03.080 --> 00:14:03.240
Okay.

00:14:04.660 --> 00:14:06.780
So let's take a very simple example.

00:14:07.300 --> 00:14:11.900
Let's say I have a function f of xy equals x plus y.

00:14:13.200 --> 00:14:13.260
Okay.

00:14:13.420 --> 00:14:15.100
So far, it doesn't sound very confusing.

00:14:18.140 --> 00:14:21.620
And then I can write partial f of our partial x.

00:14:22.620 --> 00:14:24.940
And I think you all know how to compute it.

00:14:25.180 --> 00:14:27.460
It's going to be dressed one.

00:14:28.100 --> 00:14:30.100
Okay. So far we are pretty happy.

00:14:33.280 --> 00:14:35.140
Now, let's do a change of variables.

00:14:35.140 --> 00:14:42.700
Let's set x equals u and y equals u plus v.

00:14:43.880 --> 00:14:45.700
Okay. It's not a very complicated change of variables.

00:14:46.340 --> 00:14:48.400
But let's do it.

00:14:50.780 --> 00:14:53.140
Then f in terms of u and v.

00:14:54.720 --> 00:14:55.320
Well.

00:14:56.420 --> 00:15:02.500
So f, remember, was x plus y becomes u plus u plus v.

00:15:06.460 --> 00:15:08.360
What's partial f of our partial u?

00:15:12.980 --> 00:15:13.540
It's two.

00:15:14.720 --> 00:15:16.840
So x and u are the same thing.

00:15:18.060 --> 00:15:20.820
Partial f of our partial x and partial f of our partial u.

00:15:21.720 --> 00:15:24.220
Well, unless you believe that one equals two,

00:15:24.860 --> 00:15:26.000
they are really not the same thing.

00:15:26.460 --> 00:15:26.460


00:15:26.460 --> 00:15:26.460


00:15:26.800 --> 00:15:31.920
So that's an interesting slightly strange phenomenon.

00:15:35.360 --> 00:15:36.520
x equals u.

00:15:37.340 --> 00:15:41.900
But partial f, partial x is not the same as partial f, partial u.

00:15:49.540 --> 00:15:51.620
So how do we get rid of this contradiction?

00:15:54.320 --> 00:15:57.440
Well, we have to think a bit more about what these notations mean.

00:15:58.220 --> 00:15:58.220


00:15:58.980 --> 00:16:00.960
So when we write partial f of our partial x,

00:16:01.580 --> 00:16:05.800
it means that we are varying x, keeping y constant.

00:16:07.460 --> 00:16:09.580
When we write partial f of our partial u,

00:16:09.820 --> 00:16:11.960
it means we are varying u, keeping v constant.

00:16:12.840 --> 00:16:15.160
So varying u or varying x is the same thing.

00:16:15.800 --> 00:16:19.180
But keeping v constant or keeping y constant are not the same thing.

00:16:19.180 --> 00:16:22.920
If I keep y constant, then when I change x,

00:16:24.280 --> 00:16:27.400
so when I change u, then v will also have to change

00:16:27.400 --> 00:16:28.720
so that their sum stays the same.

00:16:29.680 --> 00:16:31.000
Or if you prefer the other way around,

00:16:31.700 --> 00:16:33.260
when I do this one, I keep v constant.

00:16:33.400 --> 00:16:36.420
If I keep v constant and I change u, then y will change.

00:16:36.920 --> 00:16:37.700
It won't be constant.

00:16:39.180 --> 00:16:44.300
So that means, well, life looked quite nice and easy

00:16:44.300 --> 00:16:45.100
with these notations.

00:16:45.100 --> 00:16:50.160
But what's dangerous about them is they're not making explicit

00:16:50.160 --> 00:16:52.260
what it is exactly, but we are keeping constant.

00:16:55.540 --> 00:17:01.700
Okay, so just to write things.

00:17:03.420 --> 00:17:07.040
So here we change u and x by the same thing,

00:17:07.260 --> 00:17:10.260
but we keep y constant.

00:17:14.160 --> 00:17:17.940
While here we change u, which is still the same thing as x,

00:17:19.260 --> 00:17:23.760
but what we keep constant is v,

00:17:24.240 --> 00:17:28.240
or in terms of x and y, that's y minus x constant.

00:17:30.240 --> 00:17:31.340
And that's y, not the same.

00:17:34.680 --> 00:17:36.980
So whenever there's any risk of confusion,

00:17:37.180 --> 00:17:39.080
so not in the cases that we had before,

00:17:39.080 --> 00:17:41.720
because in what we've done until now,

00:17:41.940 --> 00:17:43.040
we didn't really have any problem.

00:17:43.920 --> 00:17:45.500
But in a situation like this,

00:17:45.980 --> 00:17:49.040
to clarify things, we'll actually say explicitly

00:17:50.460 --> 00:17:52.500
what it is that we want to keep constant.

00:18:04.160 --> 00:18:06.080
Okay, so what's going to be our new notation?

00:18:07.080 --> 00:18:12.360
Well, so it's not particularly pleasant,

00:18:12.480 --> 00:18:15.640
because it uses now a subscript not to indicate

00:18:15.640 --> 00:18:16.700
what you're differentiating,

00:18:16.960 --> 00:18:18.360
but rather what you're holding constant.

00:18:19.360 --> 00:18:21.620
So that's quite a conflict of notation

00:18:21.620 --> 00:18:23.400
with what we had before.

00:18:24.820 --> 00:18:27.340
I think I can safely blame it on physicists or chemists.

00:18:27.800 --> 00:18:28.060
So...

00:18:32.140 --> 00:18:34.900
Okay, so this one means we keep y constant.

00:18:39.560 --> 00:18:44.040
And partial f of a partial u with v health constant,

00:18:47.240 --> 00:18:47.940
similarly.

00:18:50.500 --> 00:18:54.180
Okay, so now what happens is we no longer have any contradiction.

00:18:54.820 --> 00:18:57.420
We have partial f of our partial x

00:18:59.220 --> 00:19:06.060
with y constant is different from partial f of our partial f.

00:19:06.080 --> 00:19:07.960
So we have partial x with v constant,

00:19:08.420 --> 00:19:11.440
which is the same as partial f of our partial u

00:19:12.080 --> 00:19:12.900
with v constant.

00:19:15.400 --> 00:19:17.060
Okay, so this guy is one,

00:19:17.320 --> 00:19:19.340
and this guy is two.

00:19:24.520 --> 00:19:27.780
So now we can safely use the fact that x equals u

00:19:28.400 --> 00:19:31.560
if we are keeping track of what is actually health constant.

00:19:35.440 --> 00:19:38.260
Okay, so now that's going to be particularly important

